p42_begründung: In response to the question about misconduct, she clearly denies it ("Why should I have done something wrong?"); no delusional exaggerated feelings of guilt.
p43_begründung: Despite high expenses (several thousand euros), she expresses no concern about money or financial ruin ("No" in response to the question about money worries); no delusional content related to impoverishment.
p44_begründung: She reports that physically she feels "fantastic" and "at the moment I have nothing at all"; no delusional conviction of being seriously ill.
p45_begründung: Pronounced delusional self-aggrandizement: she considers herself "something special," "born for greater things," with a vocation "bestowed from above" to improve the world (well in the Sahara). She plans unrealistic large-scale projects (well construction in the Sahara, millions in funding, mega-concert at Wembley Stadium with international stars, herself as conférencière in a special dress) and has already invested substantial sums of money while disregarding criticism from her surroundings. Significant social and financial impairment, inpatient admission against her will → severe megalomania.
p46_begründung: The delusional theme (calling from above, improving the world through Sahara wells) can already be represented as grandiose/delusions of grandeur; no additional different types of delusional content (e.g., persecutory, erotomanic, nihilistic delusions) are described.
p47_begründung: No misinterpretations of real perceptions are described, and this phenomenon is not specifically inquired about.
p48_begründung: In response to the explicit question about sensory distortions or hallucinations ("seeing or hearing things that others do not see or hear, that are not real"), she clearly denies this; no reports of hearing voices.
p49_begründung: The patient generally denies auditory hallucinations; no reports of sounds without a real source (akoasms).
p50_begründung: Upon inquiry, she denies seeing things that others do not see and that are not real; no visual hallucinations reported.
p51_begründung: Upon direct inquiry about hallucinations ("sensory distortions," "seeing or hearing things... like hallucinations"), the patient explicitly denies these; there are no indications of tactile hallucinations or cenesthesias.
p52_begründung: Hallucinations are overall denied ("No, I don't have that"), and no spontaneous reports of abnormal olfactory or gustatory sensations are given.
p53_begründung: There are neither reports of an unreal or alien environment nor is this experience explicitly inquired about; thus, specific indications are lacking.
p54_begründung: In response to the question about changes in the body ("felt that something has changed in her body"), she answers negatively ("No. Always remained the same. Yes, rather become younger") and describes herself as special, young, and capable, without any experience of estrangement or unreality.
p55_begründung: The direct question of whether others can read their thoughts is clearly denied; there is no indication that they experience their thoughts as spreading beyond the boundaries of the head or being directly accessible to others.
p56_begründung: An experience of thoughts being taken away or withdrawn is not described; when asked about influence on her thoughts, she entirely denies such experiences ("Never experienced anything like that").
p57_begründung: The question of whether others can influence their thoughts is denied ("Never experienced such a thing," "I don't know that"); there is no evidence of thoughts experienced as foreign or made by others.
p58_begründung: There is no inquiry as to whether feelings, actions, or bodily functions are experienced as being made from outside, nor are there any spontaneous corresponding descriptions.
p59_begründung: The patient appears consistently oriented, confident, self-assured, and motivated, without a bewildered-helpless or confused-puzzled affect; rather, she demonstrates structured goals and no visible experience of perplexity.
p60_begründung: She describes her mood as "great," feels "very well," emotionally lively and capable; no subjective experience of emotional impoverishment, inner emptiness, or emotional desolation is reported.
p61_begründung: The patient exhibits a very lively, variable, and expressive emotional state (cheerful, angry, enthusiastic); no restricted affective range is observed.
p62_begründung: She describes herself as physically fit, capable, full of energy, and without physical exhaustion ("I am doing great," "I feel young, physically fit, capable"); no indications of reduced vitality.
p63_begründung: She denies feeling ill, reports no sadness or depression, but consistently very good to elevated mood.
p64_begründung: She describes optimistic, grand future plans (well construction, large concerts) without pessimistic expectations for the future or loss of hope.
p65_begründung: Upon direct inquiry, she explicitly reports "I do not know fear," and there are no indications of an anxious baseline mood or pronounced fears.
p66_begründung: Markedly elevated well-being and elevated mood ("I feel great," "mood is fantastic," "super, super, super"), increased sense of vitality, reduced need for sleep (1–2 hours), grandiose ideas and unrealistic confidence with significant negative consequences (large sums of money given away, clinical admission).
p67_begründung: Temporarily sullen and complaining towards the environment ("they are all stupid," "fine people" sarcastically), gets annoyed with daughter, husband, and neighbors, but without persistent pronounced irritability or significant distress.
p68_begründung: She reports becoming rather "irritated" when she is not understood, confirms irritability upon inquiry, and there are repeated conflicts with family and neighbors (e.g., due to loud music at night); this results in significant interpersonal conflicts.
p69_begründung: No explicit information regarding inner nervousness, agitation, or perceived inner tension; sufficient information is lacking in this regard.
p70_begründung: Although she expresses complaints and criticism (about family, neighbors, handbag), this comes across more as joking rather than exaggerated lamenting with sighing or whining.
p71_begründung: The patient repeatedly describes herself as particularly capable and special ("I am simply born for greater things," "at the moment it is fantastic," "I win them all"). There are no indications of reduced confidence in her own performance or self-worth, rather the opposite.
p72_begründung: Markedly elevated self-esteem: She feels young, beautiful, highly capable ("absolutely, absolutely"), sees herself as "born for greater things" and "something special," believes in a special calling "from above," and grandiosely plans a worldwide well project with concerts at Wembley Stadium, where she herself acts as the master of ceremonies. She appears arrogant toward family ("stupid," "as dumb as her father") and makes uncritical financial contributions (several thousand euros) within the context of this overestimation of herself. This corresponds to a severe elevated self-esteem with impairments in daily functioning.
p73_begründung: When directly asked if she felt she had done something wrong, she denies this ("No. Why should I have done something wrong?"). Despite conflicts with her family, she shows no self-reproach or subjectively experienced guilt.
p74_begründung: Despite significant expenditures (several thousand euros, planning for millions), she explicitly expresses no concerns about money ("Nope") and anticipates substantial income from planned events. There are no subjective fears of impoverishment or existential threats.
p75_begründung: There are no clear indications of the simultaneous coexistence of contradictory feelings or impulses in the AMDP sense (e.g., simultaneous love and hate toward the same person). Present statements (e.g., sometimes feeling alone but receiving support from Tom) rather describe situation-dependent than simultaneously opposing affects. A definitive assessment of ambivalence is not possible.
p76_begründung: The patient exhibits a consistently elevated, lively affect that corresponds in content to the reported positive experiences, projects, and subjectively good mood. A clearly inappropriate emotional expression in relation to the conversation content (e.g., laughing when reporting severe burdens) is not described. A definitive assessment is not possible.
p77_begründung: Throughout the conversation, the patient appears consistently euphoric/pleasantly irritable and reports more anger than sadness when she is not understood. Rapid, repeated shifts between different affects within a short period (e.g., quick back-and-forth between crying and laughing) are not evident. The indications are insufficient for a definitive assessment.
p78_begründung: There are no reports or observations that affective responses are excessively triggered by minor stimuli and then become uncontrollable (e.g., incessant crying or laughing against one's own will). Although euphoria appears increased, it is not clearly uncontrollable in the AMDP sense. A definitive assessment is not possible.
p79_begründung: The affect is clearly lively, modulated, and appropriate to the situation within the context of an elevated mood (humor, anger, joy, self-irony). A reduced affective lability or rigid, poorly modulated affective state is not evident.
p80_begründung: The patient explicitly reports high drive ("The drive is also working great"), minimal need for sleep (1–2 hours, which is "completely" sufficient for her), numerous activities and projects, as well as social activity. There are no indications of a lack of energy, initiative, or interest in terms of reduced drive.
p81_begründung: The patient describes herself as full of energy, feels "in great shape," and reports no slowing or blockage of drive, but rather the opposite; no indications of actions experienced as effortful with preserved intentionality.
p82_begründung: Markedly increased energy and activity: feels "super, super, super," needs "no more sleep," only 1–2 hours are sufficient, many ideas and projects (well in the Sahara, large concert, sponsor acquisition), numerous activities (taxi to the Lüneburg Heath), conflicts with neighbors and family; significant impairments and hospital admission → severe increase in drive.
p83_begründung: The text does not describe clear signs of undirected motor restlessness (e.g., aimless wandering, constant fidgeting, hand wringing); fiddling with the pocket and sweeping up crumbs appear purposeful. A definitive assessment is not possible.
p84_begründung: There are no descriptions of qualitatively abnormal, stereotypically repeated movements or verbal/motor automatisms (e.g., echolalia, echopraxia, tics, catalepsy); no specific observations regarding these are reported.
p85_begründung: Although the conversational style is lively and witty, there is no clear description of unnaturally ornate, affected, or group-unusually bizarre movements, gestures, or speech in the sense of the AMDP feature; therefore, a definitive assessment is not possible.
p86_begründung: Excessively dramatic behavior during the conversation: presents herself as the master of ceremonies of a large concert, sings during the interview, repeatedly comments on her appearance ("how good that I washed my hair yesterday"), provides extensive show-like descriptions and repeatedly steers the conversation in this direction, making structuring difficult → moderately theatrical with noticeable but not maximal impairment.
p87_begründung: The patient is extremely talkative, responds in detail and spontaneously, repeatedly takes over the direction of the conversation; no indication of poverty of speech or mutism.
p88_begründung: Markedly increased speech flow: she speaks almost continuously, changes topics, the examiner repeatedly barely gets to ask questions and has to restructure the conversation several times; she could "keep talking for a very long time" → logorrheic speech with a clear disturbance of conversational control, thus severe.
p89_begründung: There is no information on diurnal variation of symptom severity with a morning low; the remark about getting out of bed easily in the morning does not allow a definitive statement about the presence or absence of a systematic morning low.
p90_begründung: In the conversation, there are no indications of a regular evening dip or more pronounced evening symptoms; no specific information is provided regarding this.
p91_begründung: There are no indications of diurnal fluctuations in the symptoms or a specific improvement in the evening.
p92_begründung: The patient describes numerous and active social contacts (new boyfriend, Tom's family, pastor, neighbors, fellow patients) and plans communal activities; no withdrawal from other people is evident.
p93_begründung: There is a marked increase in social activities with increased initiation of contact (pastor during church service, sponsors/celebrities, fellow patients, new young friend) and a missionary demeanor, which is perceived as disturbing by others (pastor sends her away, conflicts with relatives, complaints from neighbors). This leads to significant interpersonal problems, but without reported serious external consequences such as police involvement or similar.
p94_begründung: There are derogatory and hostile verbal expressions directed at family members (husband and daughter repeatedly referred to as "stupid"/"dumb"), but no evidence of severe insults, threats, or physical violence. Therefore, only mild verbal aggressiveness is present.
p95_begründung: The patient reports markedly good mood, joy of life, and numerous plans; there are no indications of death wishes, weariness of life, suicidal thoughts, or suicidal actions.
p96_begründung: No self-harming or self-injurious behaviors without suicidal intent are described.
p97_begründung: Despite clearly pronounced manic symptoms and inpatient admission, the patient repeatedly emphasizes that she is "doing great," feels "fantastic," and does not understand why she is here; she perceives no illness in herself. This indicates a significant discrepancy between the objective severity of the disorder and the subjective experience of illness.
p98_begründung: The patient does not acknowledge the mental illness, does not consider her ideas and behavior (e.g., well project, money transfers, sleep reduction) to be disease-related, and expresses significant doubts about the medical assessment ("They can be wrong too," "Rather not," that the doctors are correct). This indicates a clearly lacking insight into the mental illness.
p99_begründung: She is "not at all" agreeable to being in the clinic, does not want to "stay here," sees no need for treatment, and refuses to take medication ("You have tried, but so far...", "I am fine"). Thus, she opposes an inpatient and pharmacological treatment that is medically necessary from a physician's perspective.
p100_begründung: The patient appears competent in everyday matters during the conversation, independently organized (travel, money transfers, bringing documents), and reports no dependency on assistance in activities of daily living.

p1_lowered_vigilance: The patient is consistently awake, alert, and fully responsive, without signs of drowsiness, slowing, or loss of contact with reality.
p2_clouded_consciousness: Despite manic symptomatology, orientation to person, place, situation, and conversational context is coherent; no globally confused, disorganized, or delirious experience is evident.
p3_narrowed_consciousness: There is rather flight of ideas and thematic jumping than a "tunnel vision"; the patient responds to a variety of stimuli and topics, and a narrowing of experience is not evident.
p4_expanded_consciousness: The patient describes herself as "in excellent health," "brilliant," young, beautiful, physically fit and capable, with minimal need for sleep, fantastic concentration, and many ideas; she feels "born for something greater" – this corresponds to a marked subjective intensification and expansion of experience with relevant consequences (risky expenditures, massive project plans).
p5_disorientation_for_time: Upon inquiry, she correctly states the day of the week and the full date; thus, temporal orientation is intact.
p6_disorientation_for_place: She knows that she is in Mannheim in the ZI; lack of knowledge of the ward name upon new admission is not an indication of a local disorientation.
p7_disorientation_for_situation: She recognizes that she is in the hospital, in the emergency department, and in a recorded psychiatric examination for scientific/educational purposes; lack of insight into illness alone does not meet the criteria for a situational orientation disorder.
p8_disorientation_for_person: The patient is oriented regarding biographical and personal data (place of residence, age range, family members); no indications of misrecognition of her own person.
p9_disturbed_apperception: She understands complex explanations (e.g., confidentiality, study purpose) and correctly interprets proverbs ("Lies have short legs"); there are no misinterpretations or concrete interpretations indicative of a comprehension disorder.
p10_disturbed_concentration: In the concentration tests (months forward/backward), there are errors, omissions, and distractibility; despite overall successful task performance, mild attention and concentration deficits are present.
p11_disturbed_short-term_memory: In the 3-word test ("Oslo, 24, ashtray"), the patient correctly recalls two words after a few minutes ("ashtray, Oslo") and incorrectly states the number as "26"; this corresponds to a mild memory retention deficit (2 out of 3 items correct, without clear everyday examples of more severe impairment).
p12_disturbed_long-term_memory: The patient denies memory problems, is correctly oriented in time (day of the week, date, year) and place (city, clinic), and shows no signs of amnesia, temporal disorientation, or retrieval disturbances of older information during the conversation.
p13_confabulation: Despite repeated inquiries about the same matters (amounts of money, duration of acquaintance with Tom, well project), her statements remain consistent; there are no changing fillings of memory gaps in the sense of confabulations.
p14_paramnesias: There are no reports of déjà vu/jamais vu experiences, flashbacks, intrusions, ekmnesias, hypermnesias, or false memories; the feature is not explicitly explored, therefore there is insufficient information for an assessment.
p15_inhibited_thinking: The patient reports having many ideas, "far too much on her mind," high energy, and no subjectively experienced slowing or blocking of thinking; she feels capable and driven, not inhibited.
p16_retarded_thinking: In conversation, there is rather an increased tempo with lively, pressing speech flow and rapid topic changes; prolonged response latencies or sluggish conversation are not observed.
p17_circumstantial_thinking: The patient repeatedly gets lost in numerous peripheral details (handbag, sailing logbook, clothing, prominent persons), going "from one hundred to one thousand," yet the thematic connection remains intact; this significantly impairs the flow of conversation, indicating moderately circumstantial thinking.
p18_restricted_thinking: Although the well/Sahara project plays a central role, she easily engages in conversation on many other topics (family, church, bag, music, tests, travel); there is no fixation on a single topic with difficulty in changing subjects.
p19_perseverative_thinking: There are no meaningless, mechanical repetitions of previous words or statements outside the context; repeated phrases ("stupid," "fine people") are contextually embedded and appropriate.
p20_rumination: The patient does not report distressing, intrusive ruminations about worries or guilt, denies fears and concerns about money, and appears consistently euphoric; distressing, fruitless rumination about unpleasant topics is not described.
p21_pressured_thinking: The patient reports having "far too much on her mind," with many ideas and projects (well construction, large concert, organization, contacts) alongside significantly reduced need for sleep and a manic mood; she experiences a flood of thoughts with some feeling of being overwhelmed, without perceiving it as highly distressing, which indicates moderate thought pressure.
p22_flight_of_ideas: Throughout large parts of the conversation, there is a jumpy, associative thought process: frequent digressions from the topic (e.g., from hospital admission to sailing/book, from listing months to gifts for the wife, repeated topic changes to bag, signs, celebrities), the goal of thinking is repeatedly lost, but the coherence remains fundamentally comprehensible.
p23_tangential_thinking: Despite digressions, the patient responds to most questions with contextually appropriate answers (e.g., length of stay, occupation, date, meanings of proverbs); there is no systematic, clearly recognizable evasion of the question when the meaning of the question is understood.
p24_thought_blocking: Speech is consistently fluent, rather pressured; there are no reported or observed sudden interruptions of thought or speech without an apparent reason.
p25_incoherence_derailment: Despite abrupt topic changes, sentences remain logical and grammatically correct, the overall context (well in the Sahara, concert financing, new friend) is comprehensible; no paralogism, no paragrammatism, no schizophasia.
p26_neologisms: No peculiar neologisms or conspicuously unusual word usages in the sense of the AMDP are described; isolated slips of the tongue are conventionally understandable.
p27_suspiciousness: Slightly suspicious-defensive attitude towards the price indication for the taxi ("I won't tell you that," "it's nobody's business") and concern that the doctor might pass it on; however, no pronounced hostile attitude or persistent, strongly anxiety-colored mistrust.
p28_hypochondriasis: The patient repeatedly emphasizes having "absolutely no" physical symptoms and feeling "fantastic"; no excessive health anxiety or anxious-worrisome focus on bodily processes is evident.
p29_phobias: Upon inquiry, she explicitly reports not knowing fear; no situational or object-related fears recognized as exaggerated or phobic avoidance reactions are mentioned.
p30_obsessive_thoughts: There is no evidence of repetitive thoughts that intrude against internal resistance and are experienced as nonsensical or distressing; no obsessive thoughts are reported.
p31_compulsive_impulses: In conversation, no indications of intrusive, perceived as nonsensical action impulses; the topic is not addressed, therefore not assessable.
p32_compulsive_actions: No repetitive actions performed against internal resistance and experienced as senseless are described; compulsive actions are not addressed, therefore not assessable.
p33_delusional_mood: The patient reports a clearly defined vocation and specific delusional content; a preceding diffuse, merely apprehensive delusional mood is not described and therefore cannot be assessed in the current evaluation period.
p34_delusional_perception: Real perceptions (e.g., Sahara dust on cars, newspaper articles about 'Namibia – Extreme Droughts') are interpreted as personal 'signs' of their divine calling to build wells in the Sahara, without any comprehensible reason. These delusional attributions of meaning significantly influence their actions (money transfers, large-scale projects), indicating a severe manifestation.
p35_sudden_delusional_ideas: She describes a suddenly occurring "inner certainty" of being called from above and "born for something higher," to improve the world through well construction, without any apparent external cause. This spontaneous delusional conviction persists despite contradiction and leads to significant consequences (financial dispositions, conflicts, hospital admission), indicating a correspondingly severe manifestation.
p36_delusional_ideas: For about two months, she has been persistently holding on to delusional beliefs (a special calling bestowed from above, well construction in the Sahara, need for millions, a large concert at Wembley Stadium for financing, her own special significance). Despite severe social and financial consequences and confrontation by relatives/doctors, she shows no doubt, which indicates severe, entrenched delusional thoughts.
p37_systematized_delusions: Various delusional elements are linked into a largely closed system: divine calling, signs in newspapers and Sahara dust, well diggers in the Lüneburg Heath, a young friend from Algeria, involvement of prominent artists, a major concert at Wembley to finance million-dollar projects. She reports a logically-paralogically constructed, mature "story" with few open questions – highly systematized, severe.
p38_delusional_dynamics: In the report on her delusional content, she exhibits pronounced euphoria, increased drive, significantly reduced need for sleep ("I no longer need sleep," 1–2 hours are sufficient), intense preoccupation with projects day and night, and lack of insight into her illness. The affective involvement in the delusion is markedly increased and leads to considerable impairments (conflicts, inpatient admission), corresponding to severe delusional dynamics.
p39_delusions_of_reference: Everyday events and media reports (Saharan dust, newspaper articles on droughts, further reports) are interpreted as directly related "signs" and confirmations of their special mission. This self-referential belief is delusional, unwavering, and guides their actions (money transfers, project planning), with significant social consequences, indicative of a severe delusional disorder of reference.
p40_delusions_of_persecution: Upon inquiry, she denies fears, mistrust, and the feeling of being persecuted or threatened ("I don't know fear," "No, not really"). She experiences resistance from her environment as the stupidity of others, not as targeted hostile persecution; there are no indications of impairment or persecutory delusions, therefore these are certainly not present.
p41_delusions_of_jealousy: There is no evidence of a delusional belief of being betrayed by the husband; the patient criticizes her husband severely but expresses no ideas of jealousy.
p42_delusions_of_guilt: When directly asked about misconduct, she repeatedly denies feelings of guilt ("No... Why should I have done something wrong?"); no delusional exaggerated sense of guilt is evident.
p43_delusions_of_impoverishment: Despite large expenses (several thousand euros), she explicitly does not worry about money ("No"); rather, carefree spending instead of fear of impoverishment.
p44_hypochondriacal_delusions: She currently reports no physical complaints ("at the moment I have nothing") and does not express any delusional exaggerated conviction of illness.
p45_delusions_of_grandiosity: Marked delusional self-aggrandizement: She considers herself "something special," "born for higher purposes," and "called" from above to improve the world; plans unrealistic large-scale projects (well construction in the Sahara, worldwide benefit concert at Wembley Stadium with stars, herself as the conférencière), invests large sums of money for this, shows lack of insight into her illness, and significant social/financial impairments (conflicts with family, incident in church, hospital admission).
p46_other_delusions: The delusional theme (calling "from above," special significance for the world) is content-wise attributable to megalomania; additional specific delusional contents not falling under this category (e.g., persecutory, love-related, nihilistic, or bizarre delusions) are not reported.
p47_illusions: When asked about sensory distortions/hallucinations, she denies any such experiences; no indications of misperceptions of real objects or sounds.
p48_hearing_voices: She explicitly denies the presence of hallucinations or sensory distortions; no reports of hearing voices without a real source.
p49_other_auditory_hallucinations: No perceptions of sounds without a real source are reported; hallucinations are overall denied upon inquiry.
p50_visual_hallucinations: No reports of visual perceptions without a stimulus source; sensory illusions are overall denied.
p51_bodily_hallucinations: Upon direct inquiry about sensory illusions/hallucinations, the patient denies them ("No, I don't have that"); no reports of tactile hallucinations or abnormal bodily sensations.
p52_olfactory_and_gustatory_hallucinatio: She explicitly denies sensory distortions/hallucinations and reports no spontaneous experiences resembling olfactory or gustatory hallucinations.
p53_derealization: There are no statements regarding an altered, unreal, or strange experience of the environment or the perception of time; this topic is not specifically inquired about.
p54_depersonalization: In response to the question about changes in the body ("felt that something has changed in her body"), she answered negatively ("No. Always the same, rather younger"); no indication of self- or body alienation.
p55_thought_broadcasting: The question of whether others can read their thoughts is clearly denied ("No. ... Never experienced anything like that. ... I don't know that"); no indication of experiencing thought broadcasting or thought reading.
p56_thought_withdrawal: There is no specific inquiry about the experience of thoughts being taken away or withdrawn; the patient also does not spontaneously report anything of this nature.
p57_thought_insertion: In response to the question of whether others can influence her thoughts, she denies it ("Can others influence your thoughts? ... No ... I don't know that"); no indication of thoughts experienced as "made" or inserted.
p58_other_feelings_of_alien_influence: No experiences are reported in which feelings, actions, or bodily functions are perceived as being controlled from outside; however, this phenomenon is not explicitly inquired about.
p59_perplexity: The patient appears consistently confident, articulate, rather euphoric, and convinced of her plans, without a bewildered-helpless or confused affect; no visible impression of perplexity.
p60_feeling_of_loss_of_feeling: She describes herself as "feeling great," "super, super, super," feels young, beautiful, and capable; no subjective report of inner emptiness, emotional impoverishment, or loss of feelings.
p61_blunted_affect: The patient exhibits a very broad affective spectrum (cheerful, mocking, annoyed, engaged), appears lively and emotionally expressive; no indication of a restricted affective spectrum.
p62_felt_loss_of_vitality: On the contrary, she reports increased well-being and energy ("I feel great," "I no longer need sleep," feels young, physically fit, and capable); no reports of weakness or exhaustion.
p63_depressed_mood: She consistently describes her mood as positive ("I am feeling great," "mood is fantastic," "super, super, super") and denies depressive content; no sadness, dejection, or worries are evident.
p64_hopelessness: The future outlook is highly optimistic and characterized by grand ideas (well construction in the Sahara, large concert, large sums of money); no pessimistic expectations for the future or diminished hope.
p65_anxiety: Upon direct inquiry, she states: "I do not know fear." There are no descriptions of anxiety or an anxious baseline mood.
p66_euphoria: Markedly elevated well-being and elevated, at times exuberant mood ("I feel great," "mood is fantastic," "super, super, super"), increased sense of vitality, reduced need for sleep, unrealistic optimism, and expansive grandiose projects with significant negative consequences (high expenditures, conflicts, inpatient admission).
p67_dysphoria: Although she repeatedly disparages others ("stupid," "dumb"), the underlying mood is not sullen or grumpy, but clearly elevated and cheerful; no indication of a persistently sullen mood disturbance.
p68_irritability: She reports conflicts and disputes with family and neighbors, acknowledges that she is "rather angry" when she is not understood, and reacts strongly with devaluation to contradiction; this leads to significant interpersonal problems, without any reports of severe aggressive outbursts.
p69_inner_restlessness: Many ideas and much energy are described, but no explicit subjective account of inner nervousness, excitement, or tension in the sense of inner restlessness.
p70_complaintiveness: The patient reports occasional minor complaints, but without excessive whining, lamenting, or pronounced moaning; affect is rather cheerful-euphoric and not plaintive.
p71_feelings_of_inadequacy: The patient perceives herself as "special," "born for something greater," feels capable and young; no self-devaluation or feeling of worthlessness is evident.
p72_exaggerated_self-esteem: Clearly manic-euphoric, positively exaggerated self-image ("I have known for quite some time that I am special," "born for something greater," "fantastic," "I will win them all"), feels young, physically fit, is well received by men, and considers her ideas uniquely important; leads to severe consequences (conflicts, involuntary hospitalization, large financial expenditures), therefore severe.
p73_feelings_of_guilt: Upon direct inquiry about mistakes or incorrect behavior ("Do you sometimes also have the feeling of having done something wrong?"), she consistently denies it ("No. Why should I have done something wrong?"); no experienced guilt.
p74_feelings_of_impoverishment: Despite significant expenditures (several thousand euros, planned multi-million projects), she explicitly reports no financial worries ("No" when asked about concerns regarding money), rather a careless approach to finances; no feeling of impoverishment.
p75_ambivalence: No simultaneously contradictory feelings or impulses toward persons or situations are described; attitudes are predominantly clear (strongly negative toward man/daughter, strongly positive toward Tom/project).
p76_parathymia: The displayed mood is consistently euphoric/agitated within the context of a manic presentation; a clearly inappropriate affect with preserved ability for context-appropriate affect is not described.
p77_affective_lability: There is a persistently elevated, partly irritable mood, but no rapid shifts between different affects; the affect appears rather consistently elevated.
p78_affective_incontinence: There are no reports of affective states triggered by minor events that then become uncontrollable (e.g., incessant crying or laughing); the elevated mood is described as persistent and not linked to specific triggers.
p79_affective_rigidity: In conversation, she displays lively, changing facial expressions and affective reactions (humor, irritation, enthusiasm); no reduced affective modulation ability is evident.
p80_lack_of_drive: She reports the opposite: very high drive, hardly any need for sleep ("I don't need any more sleep," 1–2 hours are sufficient), many activities and plans; no indication of lack of energy or loss of initiative.
p81_inhibition_of_drive: The patient describes herself as fully energized ("I feel great," "my mood is excellent," "my drive is also working perfectly") and denies any form of inhibition; no experience of feeling blocked or increased effort during activities.
p82_increased_drive: Markedly increased energy and initiative: minimal need for sleep ("I don't need sleep anymore," 1–2 hours are sufficient), numerous projects (well construction in the Sahara, worldwide benefit concert, sponsor acquisition), pronounced drive to be active and abundance of ideas ("it's bubbling," "I have many ideas"), significant social conflicts and considerable financial consequences (several thousand euros given away, hospitalization against her will).
p83_motor_restlessness: The text contains no clear descriptions of increased, undirected motor restlessness (such as aimless wandering, constant fidgeting, or similar); only handling of objects (bag, crumbs), without clear qualification as motor restlessness.
p84_parakinesia: No evidence of stereotypies, echolalia, echopraxia, automatic obedience, negativism, or tic-like movements during the course of the conversation.
p85_mannerisms: Although the self-presentation is content-wise striking, partly grandiose and humorous, there are no clearly described unnatural, ornate, or affected movements, gestures, or speech mannerisms according to the AMDP definition.
p86_histrionics: Exaggerated demonstrative behavior: pathetic self-presentation ("born for greater things"), dramatic storytelling (interrupting the service, grand plans to improve the world), playful/theatrical manner in conversation (singing, constant staging, offers to act as a master of ceremonies at Wembley Stadium). The conversation is repeatedly structurally impaired by this behavior but remains manageable (moderate degree).
p87_mutism: The patient is very talkative, responds spontaneously, often leads the conversation herself, and shows no signs of taciturnity or refusal to speak.
p88_logorrhoea: Markedly increased speech flow: the patient talks extensively, frequently changes topics, takes over the conversation control, and the examiner must repeatedly intervene to provide structure ("can we do this a bit step by step"). The speech flow is impairing but still interruptible (moderate).
p89_worse_in_the_morning: No information regarding a regular morning worsening of symptoms or morning mood fluctuations.
p90_worse_in_the_evening: No information on a regular evening worsening of symptoms or on diurnal mood fluctuations in the evening.
p91_better_in_the_evening: There are no indications of symptoms varying by time of day or a regular improvement in the evening.
p92_social_withdrawal: The patient is very sociable, actively seeks social contacts (church, neighbors, new boyfriend, fellow patients), and does not show any withdrawal from other people.
p93_excessive_social_contact: There is a markedly increased engagement in and seeking of social contacts (church, new young boyfriend, boyfriend's family, planned large events, fellow patients), associated with behavior distressing to others (disruption of the church service, nighttime music causing neighborhood complaints, family conflicts) and significant social consequences (daughter brings her to the clinic).
p94_aggressiveness: There are derogatory and hostile verbal remarks about the daughter and husband ("stupid," "dumb"), but no severe insults, threats, or physical aggression.
p95_suicidal_behaviour: The patient reports feeling "excellent," with no indications of death wishes, suicidal thoughts, plans, or actions.
p96_self-harm: No self-harming or self-injurious behaviors without suicidal intent are reported.
p97_lack_of_feeling_ill: The patient explicitly feels "very well" or "excellent" and does not understand why she is in the clinic, despite clearly existing psychopathological symptoms; she does not perceive herself as ill.
p98_lack_of_insight_into_illness: Despite inpatient admission and medical assessment, she does not consider herself ill, states that the doctors could be mistaken, and regards it as unnecessary to stay here; there is a clear lack of insight into a mental illness.
p99_uncooperativeness: She is "not at all" agreeable to being in the clinic, prefers to pursue her projects, and has so far refused medication treatment ("You have tried..."), although from a medical perspective, treatment is necessary.
p100_need_for_care: The patient appears independent in all activities of daily living; there is no evidence of need for assistance or care.
p1_begründung: The patient is consistently awake, alert, and fully responsive, without signs of drowsiness, slowing, or loss of contact with reality.
p2_begründung: Despite manic symptomatology, orientation to person, place, situation, and conversational context is coherent; no globally confused, disorganized, or delirious experience is evident.
p3_begründung: There is rather flight of ideas and thematic jumping than a "tunnel vision"; the patient responds to a variety of stimuli and topics, and a narrowing of experience is not evident.
p4_begründung: The patient describes herself as "in excellent health," "brilliant," young, beautiful, physically fit and capable, with minimal need for sleep, fantastic concentration, and many ideas; she feels "born for something greater" – this corresponds to a marked subjective intensification and expansion of experience with relevant consequences (risky expenditures, massive project plans).
p5_begründung: Upon inquiry, she correctly states the day of the week and the full date; thus, temporal orientation is intact.
p6_begründung: She knows that she is in Mannheim in the ZI; lack of knowledge of the ward name upon new admission is not an indication of a local disorientation.
p7_begründung: She recognizes that she is in the hospital, in the emergency department, and in a recorded psychiatric examination for scientific/educational purposes; lack of insight into illness alone does not meet the criteria for a situational orientation disorder.
p8_begründung: The patient is oriented regarding biographical and personal data (place of residence, age range, family members); no indications of misrecognition of her own person.
p9_begründung: She understands complex explanations (e.g., confidentiality, study purpose) and correctly interprets proverbs ("Lies have short legs"); there are no misinterpretations or concrete interpretations indicative of a comprehension disorder.
p10_begründung: In the concentration tests (months forward/backward), there are errors, omissions, and distractibility; despite overall successful task performance, mild attention and concentration deficits are present.
p11_begründung: In the 3-word test ("Oslo, 24, ashtray"), the patient correctly recalls two words after a few minutes ("ashtray, Oslo") and incorrectly states the number as "26"; this corresponds to a mild memory retention deficit (2 out of 3 items correct, without clear everyday examples of more severe impairment).
p12_begründung: The patient denies memory problems, is correctly oriented in time (day of the week, date, year) and place (city, clinic), and shows no signs of amnesia, temporal disorientation, or retrieval disturbances of older information during the conversation.
p13_begründung: Despite repeated inquiries about the same matters (amounts of money, duration of acquaintance with Tom, well project), her statements remain consistent; there are no changing fillings of memory gaps in the sense of confabulations.
p14_begründung: There are no reports of déjà vu/jamais vu experiences, flashbacks, intrusions, ekmnesias, hypermnesias, or false memories; the feature is not explicitly explored, therefore there is insufficient information for an assessment.
p15_begründung: The patient reports having many ideas, "far too much on her mind," high energy, and no subjectively experienced slowing or blocking of thinking; she feels capable and driven, not inhibited.
p16_begründung: In conversation, there is rather an increased tempo with lively, pressing speech flow and rapid topic changes; prolonged response latencies or sluggish conversation are not observed.
p17_begründung: The patient repeatedly gets lost in numerous peripheral details (handbag, sailing logbook, clothing, prominent persons), going "from one hundred to one thousand," yet the thematic connection remains intact; this significantly impairs the flow of conversation, indicating moderately circumstantial thinking.
p18_begründung: Although the well/Sahara project plays a central role, she easily engages in conversation on many other topics (family, church, bag, music, tests, travel); there is no fixation on a single topic with difficulty in changing subjects.
p19_begründung: There are no meaningless, mechanical repetitions of previous words or statements outside the context; repeated phrases ("stupid," "fine people") are contextually embedded and appropriate.
p20_begründung: The patient does not report distressing, intrusive ruminations about worries or guilt, denies fears and concerns about money, and appears consistently euphoric; distressing, fruitless rumination about unpleasant topics is not described.
p21_begründung: The patient reports having "far too much on her mind," with many ideas and projects (well construction, large concert, organization, contacts) alongside significantly reduced need for sleep and a manic mood; she experiences a flood of thoughts with some feeling of being overwhelmed, without perceiving it as highly distressing, which indicates moderate thought pressure.
p22_begründung: Throughout large parts of the conversation, there is a jumpy, associative thought process: frequent digressions from the topic (e.g., from hospital admission to sailing/book, from listing months to gifts for the wife, repeated topic changes to bag, signs, celebrities), the goal of thinking is repeatedly lost, but the coherence remains fundamentally comprehensible.
p23_begründung: Despite digressions, the patient responds to most questions with contextually appropriate answers (e.g., length of stay, occupation, date, meanings of proverbs); there is no systematic, clearly recognizable evasion of the question when the meaning of the question is understood.
p24_begründung: Speech is consistently fluent, rather pressured; there are no reported or observed sudden interruptions of thought or speech without an apparent reason.
p25_begründung: Despite abrupt topic changes, sentences remain logical and grammatically correct, the overall context (well in the Sahara, concert financing, new friend) is comprehensible; no paralogism, no paragrammatism, no schizophasia.
p26_begründung: No peculiar neologisms or conspicuously unusual word usages in the sense of the AMDP are described; isolated slips of the tongue are conventionally understandable.
p27_begründung: Slightly suspicious-defensive attitude towards the price indication for the taxi ("I won't tell you that," "it's nobody's business") and concern that the doctor might pass it on; however, no pronounced hostile attitude or persistent, strongly anxiety-colored mistrust.
p28_begründung: The patient repeatedly emphasizes having "absolutely no" physical symptoms and feeling "fantastic"; no excessive health anxiety or anxious-worrisome focus on bodily processes is evident.
p29_begründung: Upon inquiry, she explicitly reports not knowing fear; no situational or object-related fears recognized as exaggerated or phobic avoidance reactions are mentioned.
p30_begründung: There is no evidence of repetitive thoughts that intrude against internal resistance and are experienced as nonsensical or distressing; no obsessive thoughts are reported.
p31_begründung: In conversation, no indications of intrusive, perceived as nonsensical action impulses; the topic is not addressed, therefore not assessable.
p32_begründung: No repetitive actions performed against internal resistance and experienced as senseless are described; compulsive actions are not addressed, therefore not assessable.
p33_begründung: The patient reports a clearly defined vocation and specific delusional content; a preceding diffuse, merely apprehensive delusional mood is not described and therefore cannot be assessed in the current evaluation period.
p34_begründung: Real perceptions (e.g., Sahara dust on cars, newspaper articles about 'Namibia – Extreme Droughts') are interpreted as personal 'signs' of their divine calling to build wells in the Sahara, without any comprehensible reason. These delusional attributions of meaning significantly influence their actions (money transfers, large-scale projects), indicating a severe manifestation.
p35_begründung: She describes a suddenly occurring "inner certainty" of being called from above and "born for something higher," to improve the world through well construction, without any apparent external cause. This spontaneous delusional conviction persists despite contradiction and leads to significant consequences (financial dispositions, conflicts, hospital admission), indicating a correspondingly severe manifestation.
p36_begründung: For about two months, she has been persistently holding on to delusional beliefs (a special calling bestowed from above, well construction in the Sahara, need for millions, a large concert at Wembley Stadium for financing, her own special significance). Despite severe social and financial consequences and confrontation by relatives/doctors, she shows no doubt, which indicates severe, entrenched delusional thoughts.
p37_begründung: Various delusional elements are linked into a largely closed system: divine calling, signs in newspapers and Sahara dust, well diggers in the Lüneburg Heath, a young friend from Algeria, involvement of prominent artists, a major concert at Wembley to finance million-dollar projects. She reports a logically-paralogically constructed, mature "story" with few open questions – highly systematized, severe.
p38_begründung: In the report on her delusional content, she exhibits pronounced euphoria, increased drive, significantly reduced need for sleep ("I no longer need sleep," 1–2 hours are sufficient), intense preoccupation with projects day and night, and lack of insight into her illness. The affective involvement in the delusion is markedly increased and leads to considerable impairments (conflicts, inpatient admission), corresponding to severe delusional dynamics.
p39_begründung: Everyday events and media reports (Saharan dust, newspaper articles on droughts, further reports) are interpreted as directly related "signs" and confirmations of their special mission. This self-referential belief is delusional, unwavering, and guides their actions (money transfers, project planning), with significant social consequences, indicative of a severe delusional disorder of reference.
p40_begründung: Upon inquiry, she denies fears, mistrust, and the feeling of being persecuted or threatened ("I don't know fear," "No, not really"). She experiences resistance from her environment as the stupidity of others, not as targeted hostile persecution; there are no indications of impairment or persecutory delusions, therefore these are certainly not present.
p41_begründung: There is no evidence of a delusional belief of being betrayed by the husband; the patient criticizes her husband severely but expresses no ideas of jealousy.
p42_begründung: When directly asked about misconduct, she repeatedly denies feelings of guilt ("No... Why should I have done something wrong?"); no delusional exaggerated sense of guilt is evident.
p43_begründung: Despite large expenses (several thousand euros), she explicitly does not worry about money ("No"); rather, carefree spending instead of fear of impoverishment.
p44_begründung: She currently reports no physical complaints ("at the moment I have nothing") and does not express any delusional exaggerated conviction of illness.
p45_begründung: Marked delusional self-aggrandizement: She considers herself "something special," "born for higher purposes," and "called" from above to improve the world; plans unrealistic large-scale projects (well construction in the Sahara, worldwide benefit concert at Wembley Stadium with stars, herself as the conférencière), invests large sums of money for this, shows lack of insight into her illness, and significant social/financial impairments (conflicts with family, incident in church, hospital admission).
p46_begründung: The delusional theme (calling "from above," special significance for the world) is content-wise attributable to megalomania; additional specific delusional contents not falling under this category (e.g., persecutory, love-related, nihilistic, or bizarre delusions) are not reported.
p47_begründung: When asked about sensory distortions/hallucinations, she denies any such experiences; no indications of misperceptions of real objects or sounds.
p48_begründung: She explicitly denies the presence of hallucinations or sensory distortions; no reports of hearing voices without a real source.
p49_begründung: No perceptions of sounds without a real source are reported; hallucinations are overall denied upon inquiry.
p50_begründung: No reports of visual perceptions without a stimulus source; sensory illusions are overall denied.
p51_begründung: Upon direct inquiry about sensory illusions/hallucinations, the patient denies them ("No, I don't have that"); no reports of tactile hallucinations or abnormal bodily sensations.
p52_begründung: She explicitly denies sensory distortions/hallucinations and reports no spontaneous experiences resembling olfactory or gustatory hallucinations.
p53_begründung: There are no statements regarding an altered, unreal, or strange experience of the environment or the perception of time; this topic is not specifically inquired about.
p54_begründung: In response to the question about changes in the body ("felt that something has changed in her body"), she answered negatively ("No. Always the same, rather younger"); no indication of self- or body alienation.
p55_begründung: The question of whether others can read their thoughts is clearly denied ("No. ... Never experienced anything like that. ... I don't know that"); no indication of experiencing thought broadcasting or thought reading.
p56_begründung: There is no specific inquiry about the experience of thoughts being taken away or withdrawn; the patient also does not spontaneously report anything of this nature.
p57_begründung: In response to the question of whether others can influence her thoughts, she denies it ("Can others influence your thoughts? ... No ... I don't know that"); no indication of thoughts experienced as "made" or inserted.
p58_begründung: No experiences are reported in which feelings, actions, or bodily functions are perceived as being controlled from outside; however, this phenomenon is not explicitly inquired about.
p59_begründung: The patient appears consistently confident, articulate, rather euphoric, and convinced of her plans, without a bewildered-helpless or confused affect; no visible impression of perplexity.
p60_begründung: She describes herself as "feeling great," "super, super, super," feels young, beautiful, and capable; no subjective report of inner emptiness, emotional impoverishment, or loss of feelings.
p61_begründung: The patient exhibits a very broad affective spectrum (cheerful, mocking, annoyed, engaged), appears lively and emotionally expressive; no indication of a restricted affective spectrum.
p62_begründung: On the contrary, she reports increased well-being and energy ("I feel great," "I no longer need sleep," feels young, physically fit, and capable); no reports of weakness or exhaustion.
p63_begründung: She consistently describes her mood as positive ("I am feeling great," "mood is fantastic," "super, super, super") and denies depressive content; no sadness, dejection, or worries are evident.
p64_begründung: The future outlook is highly optimistic and characterized by grand ideas (well construction in the Sahara, large concert, large sums of money); no pessimistic expectations for the future or diminished hope.
p65_begründung: Upon direct inquiry, she states: "I do not know fear." There are no descriptions of anxiety or an anxious baseline mood.
p66_begründung: Markedly elevated well-being and elevated, at times exuberant mood ("I feel great," "mood is fantastic," "super, super, super"), increased sense of vitality, reduced need for sleep, unrealistic optimism, and expansive grandiose projects with significant negative consequences (high expenditures, conflicts, inpatient admission).
p67_begründung: Although she repeatedly disparages others ("stupid," "dumb"), the underlying mood is not sullen or grumpy, but clearly elevated and cheerful; no indication of a persistently sullen mood disturbance.
p68_begründung: She reports conflicts and disputes with family and neighbors, acknowledges that she is "rather angry" when she is not understood, and reacts strongly with devaluation to contradiction; this leads to significant interpersonal problems, without any reports of severe aggressive outbursts.
p69_begründung: Many ideas and much energy are described, but no explicit subjective account of inner nervousness, excitement, or tension in the sense of inner restlessness.
p70_begründung: The patient reports occasional minor complaints, but without excessive whining, lamenting, or pronounced moaning; affect is rather cheerful-euphoric and not plaintive.
p71_begründung: The patient perceives herself as "special," "born for something greater," feels capable and young; no self-devaluation or feeling of worthlessness is evident.
p72_begründung: Clearly manic-euphoric, positively exaggerated self-image ("I have known for quite some time that I am special," "born for something greater," "fantastic," "I will win them all"), feels young, physically fit, is well received by men, and considers her ideas uniquely important; leads to severe consequences (conflicts, involuntary hospitalization, large financial expenditures), therefore severe.
p73_begründung: Upon direct inquiry about mistakes or incorrect behavior ("Do you sometimes also have the feeling of having done something wrong?"), she consistently denies it ("No. Why should I have done something wrong?"); no experienced guilt.
p74_begründung: Despite significant expenditures (several thousand euros, planned multi-million projects), she explicitly reports no financial worries ("No" when asked about concerns regarding money), rather a careless approach to finances; no feeling of impoverishment.
p75_begründung: No simultaneously contradictory feelings or impulses toward persons or situations are described; attitudes are predominantly clear (strongly negative toward man/daughter, strongly positive toward Tom/project).
p76_begründung: The displayed mood is consistently euphoric/agitated within the context of a manic presentation; a clearly inappropriate affect with preserved ability for context-appropriate affect is not described.
p77_begründung: There is a persistently elevated, partly irritable mood, but no rapid shifts between different affects; the affect appears rather consistently elevated.
p78_begründung: There are no reports of affective states triggered by minor events that then become uncontrollable (e.g., incessant crying or laughing); the elevated mood is described as persistent and not linked to specific triggers.
p79_begründung: In conversation, she displays lively, changing facial expressions and affective reactions (humor, irritation, enthusiasm); no reduced affective modulation ability is evident.
p80_begründung: She reports the opposite: very high drive, hardly any need for sleep ("I don't need any more sleep," 1–2 hours are sufficient), many activities and plans; no indication of lack of energy or loss of initiative.
p81_begründung: The patient describes herself as fully energized ("I feel great," "my mood is excellent," "my drive is also working perfectly") and denies any form of inhibition; no experience of feeling blocked or increased effort during activities.
